    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>Dec. 22<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> 1881</date>
                    <salute>Dear Surman</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have heard from D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Günther &amp; your case is hopeless, as he says “<hi rend="underline">please note, that the man must not be beyond 30 years age</hi>”.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Moreover the permission of one of the 3 <hi rend="doubleUnderline">chief</hi> Trustees must be obtained before even application can be made, &amp; I have no influence whatever on the Archbishop, the Chancellor &amp; Speaker.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I am sorry that you sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be disappointed &amp; remain | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p>
<p>D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. G. says that the applications is very great.—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway</hi> … <hi rend="italic">S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13574.xml">letter from Albert Günther, 21 December 1881</ref>. In 1881, Surman would have been 31.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13574.xml">letter from Albert Günther, 21 December 1881</ref> and n. 2. <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4651.xml">Archibald Campbell Tait</ref> was the archbishop of Canterbury, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3657.xml">Roundell Palmer</ref> was the lord chancellor, and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_8730.xml">Henry Brand</ref> was the speaker of the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_7863.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">House of Commons</ref>.</note>
        </div> 
     
